# All shiny things do fade
I have to admit I had fun doing this and I understand why people are excited about the potential of this type of creation. I am unfortunately an ideas guy and it feels like this was purpose-built for me. Ezra Klein recently wrote about how using AI changes us and discusses cognitive offloading and cognitive surrender. As an ideas guy who will never accomplish all I want to, I am happy to offload cognitive burden and, in many cases, I think I will be happy to surrender cognitive control over an idea to . The question then becomes one of taste. What will I offload, what will I surrender, and what will I maintain complete control over? Even now, as I am writing this in VSCode, copilot is attempting to complete my sentences. I am not sure how to turn this off and I have staved off all suggestions. So I guess writing at least is one responsibility I will keep.

I imagine the luster of this experience will fade. In fact, it already had by the time I was wrapping this up. Like any new tech, it will become commonplace, commodified. In this case, a part of our every day work life. What then remains? The joy of seeing ones ideas come to fruition is one. But one important aspect of this feeling has always been that one's hard work has paid off. If I am not doing the hard work, will I feel the same joy? 